msItem.title: Maḥzor le-Yom Kipur ke-minhag ḳehilat Liśla?
[מחזור ליום כפור כמנהג לישלא?]

author.name: Moldovan Family Judaica Collection (University of Pennsylvania)

support.watermark: Crown above a cartouche with illegible name above a bell (for example, f. 21, 101, 130)

supportDesc.extent: 257 leaves : 180 x 125 (145 x 90) mm bound to 185 x 135 mm

collation.p: Paper, 257 + i; 1-5⁸ 6¹⁴ 7-13⁸ 14⁸ (-6, -7) 15⁸ 16⁸ (-7) 17-31⁸ 32⁶ ; modern foliation in pencil, lower left recto, 1-257.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 20-21 unruled long lines with standard Maḥzor layout; for certain piyutim, the layout is in double-columns with skipped lines between stanzas (such as f. 129r-130v); quarto format.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a Provençal cursive script, with portions vocalized and unvocalized; certain passages are written in Italian square script (for example, the paragraph opening the Kol Nidre service, f. 2r; the colophon, f. 255v).

binding.p: Green sheepskin, likely original, with the leather deteriorating; spine head and tail damaged. Evidence of old water damage inside boards.

origin.p: Written in the Comtat Venaissin in the Provence region of France, signed on 24 Adar (2) 5423, or Monday April 2, 1663, by "Eliyahu Dalfogeṭ" (f. 255v); Benjamin Richler spells the scribe's name as Delpuget; see Richler, B., Hebrew Manuscripts in the Bibliotheca Palatina in Parma (Jerusalem: Hebrew University, Hamakor, 2001), pg. 291 (no. 1111, Parma 3491).

history.provenance: Presented to The Penn Libraries in 2018 by Joseph and Susan Moldovan (C'76).
